@148 = ~Pung~

@150 = ~Gnomish Boots~
@151 = ~These low boots are cobbled from the sturdiest leather. The toes point upward slightly, and the soles are designed to keep a sure footing on any terrain, whether underground or on the surface.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability: Immune to Entangle, Grease and Web
Weight: 2~

@152 = ~Ruby~
@153 = ~The ruby is a clear to deep crimson corundum stone, the hardest next to the diamond. The deeper the red, the more valuable the stone, so that more valuable variations are easily identified. Most higher quality rubies come from deep underground. Rubies are supposed to grant good luck, according to superstitions in the Sea of Fallen Stars. In magical research, rubies are often ground to produce magical dust and inks, and also are associated with combatting the undead, and thus adorn devices made for this purpose.~

@154 = ~Star Ruby~
@155 = ~This magnificent ruby is a stone of unparalleled value. The star at its center radiates at different angles as the stone rotates, throwing a blood-red light in all directions. A gem this rare and beautiful could ransom a prince.~

@156 = ~Pickaxe~
@157 = ~The military pick originated from the common mining tool. It consists of a heavy piercing fluke mounted on a haft. Its role in combat is to puncture heavier armors, even full plate.

Damage: 2D4
Damage type: piercing
Weight: 6
Speed Factor: 7
Proficiency Type: Axe
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 8 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Druid
 Cleric
 Mage 
 Thief~

@158 = ~Svirfneblin Pickaxe~
@159 = ~The deep gnomes are fond of these weapons for obvious reasons: they are ideal for digging precious gems from the earth. Pickaxes also ideal for piercing heavy armor, even full plate. The svirfneblin make their picks from a strong, light alloy of unknown properties. This metal keeps a sharp edge even after vigorous mining or combat.

THAC0: +1
Damage: 2D4 + 1
Damage type: piercing
Weight: 5
Speed Factor: 6
Proficiency Type: Axe
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 7 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Druid
 Cleric
 Mage 
 Thief~

@160 = ~Svirfneblin Club~
@161 = ~This unusual weapon lies midway between a club and mace, with some features of a morning star. Its spherical head is studded with knobs of various sizes, which the deep gnomes use to do detailed stone work. The head joins the haft as one piece of alloyed metal, and lacks the flanges of a mace. Thus, it wields more like a club than any other weapon.

THAC0: +1
Damage: 1D6 + 2
Damage type: crushing
Weight: 3
Speed Factor: 3
Proficiency Type: Club
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 5 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Mage~

@162 = ~This bottle holds a concoction of unknown vintage. It is said that an adventurer from Scornubel once quaffed such an unknown vintage that turned out to be homemade mushroom wine from the Wood of Sharp Teeth. The man disappeared for a decade and turned up later in a fishing shack on the isle of Snowdown with absolutely no memory of his past. Hopefully, this is not such a vintage, but it might be safest to identify it before drinking.~

@163 = ~Gogondy~
@164 = ~This wrought iron bottle has a granite stopper and is inscribed with strange runes in the svirfneblin language. It contains a strange, heady-smelling drink that is deep red in color. The deep gnomes prize this wine for its mystical properties, which extend beyond the ken of other races.

Special: Unknown
Weight: 1~

@165 = ~This wrought iron bottle has a garnet stopper and is inscribed with mystical runes in the svirfneblin language. It contains a strange, pungent-smelling drink that is deep red in color. The deep gnomes prize this wine for its power to grant visions. This particular vintage is toned down to allow non-svirfneblin to benefit from these visions, though the exact nature of the vision varies for each imbiber.

Special: Unknown
Weight: 1~

@166 = ~Strawberry Wine~
@167 = ~This is a superior vintage from a crop harvested from the shores of Lake Esmel over a decade ago, in the Year of the Worm (1356). Quite dry for a berry wine, it has a sparkling afterbite with hints of clove and orange zest. Its aroma evokes fresh strawberries, dry oak and spring rain. Elegant and medium-bodied, it offers a rare chance to relax in the midst of the wilderness. It is said to pair exceptionally well with Calishite pheasant.

Special:
 Drunkenness +20% for 3 turns
 Resist Fear for 3 turns
 Charisma +1 or -1 (50% chance for each)
Weight: 1~

@168 = ~Berries~
@169 = ~Various sorts of berries grow throughout all of Abeir-Toril, from the common blackberry to the fairly rare solik berry. Some berries are poisonous, so it may be wise to figure out what these berries are before munching on them.~

@170 = ~Gooseberries~
@171 = ~Gooseberries are indigenous to western Faerûn, and flourish from Waterdeep to Chult to the Utter East. Although somewhat tart, bitter and sour when raw, gooseberries are highly-coveted for their nutritional properties. Many Faerûnians eat them fresh and use them in pies, tarts and jams as well.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 50% chance heals 5 hit points
 25% chance fatigue -50%
 25% chance regenerates 1 hit point per round for 1 turn
Weight: 0~

@172 = ~Pie~
@173 = ~Pies are large pastries typically filled with fruit, though some are made with cream, spices or even more exotic substances. This one looks and smells delicious.~

@174 = ~Gooseberry Pie~
@175 = ~Karaea's favorite pie derives from a recipe she learned shortly after coming to the surface. Though by this point, she has altered it to make it truly her own. This sweet-tart pie pleases from the first bite.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 Fatigue set to 0
 Regenerates 1 hit point per round for 5 turns
 Saving throws -5 for 5 turns
Weight: 1~

@176 = ~Bread and Jam~
@177 = ~This thick slice of freshly baked bread is spread with rich, creamy butter and topped with a generous dollop of jam. It is a simple, heartening treat.

STATISTICS:

Special: Fatigue -50%
Weight: 1~

@178 = ~Jam~
@179 = ~This is a jar of jam. Could be almost any flavor - you'll never know until you check it out!~

@180 = ~Apple Butter~
@181 = ~Crisp, tart apples picked in the late fall and spiced with Karaea's secret blend (one that definitely includes more than a hint of nutmeg) make a truly delightful spread. On opening the jar, the traveler is pleasantly reminded of home, hearth and family.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 Cures disease
 Reduces drunkenness by half
Weight: 1~

@182 = ~Blackberry Jam~
@183 = ~Blackberries grow wild throughout most of northern Faerûn, making it easy for the discerning jam-maker to choose the very best. Only the darkest, ripest berries were used making this exceptional spread, the quintessential jam.

Should you accidentally stain your clothing, try pouring boiling water through the stained area and bleaching it in the sunlight. Alternately, you may purchase an inexpensive deep purple dye from your local dye merchant and give your clothing a whole new look.

STATISTICS:

Special: Cures poison
Weight: 1~

@184 = ~Blueberry Jam~
@185 = ~Introduced by some of the first explorers of Maztica, the blueberry rapidly spread throughout the northern Sword Coast. Jam-makers quickly added it to their repertoire. An exceptionally sweet crop of blueberries, straight from the field, went into this delectable jam. Sweet, with just a hint of refreshing tartness, it energizes you almost as soon as you taste it.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 Constitution +1 for 2 turns
 Cures feeblemind
Weight: 1~

@186 = ~Goodberry Jam~
@187 = ~An ingenious combination of spellcrafting and cookery leads to this delicious spread. One bite and you feel better at once.

STATISTICS:

Special: Heals 18 hit points
Weight: 1~

@188 = ~Lingonberry Jam~
@189 = ~Lingonberries grow in colder climates, such as the Moonshae Isles and Icewind Dale. The red fruits are quite tart, but are cooked and sweetened to make excellent jams, juices and syrups. Northerners prize the berries for their helpful properties in the frigid north. 

Karaea has only recently begun to experiment with this fruit, using recipes borrowed from others. The result is a hard-to-resist spread that will warm the cockles of your heart (if you have one).

STATISTICS:

Special:
 Protection from Cold +65% for 2 turns
 5% chance to cause temporary insanity (Berserk) for 2 rounds
Weight: 1~

@190 = ~Mulberry Jam~
@191 = ~The mulberry is thought to have originated in the Shining South, though it is now so widespread that determining its exact point of origin is no longer possible. The sweet, dark purple jam made from the fruit makes your mouth water. 

Unfortunately, while the ripe fruit is a healthy snack, the unripe fruit occasionally produces hallucinations. You take your chances with this jam.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 Protection from Fire +65% for 2 turns
 5% chance to cause hallucinations (Horror) for 2 rounds
Weight: 1~

@192 = ~Raspberry Jam~
@193 = ~Originally brought from far eastern Koryo and the Ama Basin, the raspberry has gradually spread westward to become one of the more popular berries in Faerûn. This jam is made from the finest ruby-red raspberries, picked just at the height of their sweetness. It brings back memories of hot summer days. The jam's healthful properties include better eyesight and clarity of vision.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 Infravision for 2 turns
 Cures blindness
Weight: 1~

@194 = ~Strawberry Jam~
@195 = ~Ever since this succulent fruit from Maztica was introduced in Faerûn, it has been a favorite. People from all walks of life adopted it for its excellence in jams, pies and even wines. This jam, made only from the ripest, reddest berries, will please even the most jaded palates.

STATISTICS:

Special: Protection from Acid +50% for 2 turns
Weight: 1~

@196 = ~Wolfberry Jam~
@197 = ~The wolfberry is popular in Shou Lung, where the dried berries are added to rice pudding or brewed to make tea or even ale. The bright red berry has spread west to become popular in Faerûn, where it grows wild in hedges and can be easily gathered by wandering merchants and jam-makers.

STATISTICS:

Special:
 75% chance for Lesser Restoration
 10% chance fatigue +25%
Weight: 1~

@198 = ~Rapier~
@199 = ~The rapier is a straight, double-edged, pointed blade with an elaborate hilt. It is designed to be a light, thrusting sword. The term "rapier" is often used to describe a civilian weapon, as opposed to the heavier and deadlier swords of soldiers and mercenaries. Rapiers are fashionable among nobles and particularly among duelists and fencers.

STATISTICS:

Damage: 1D6 + 1
Damage Type: Piercing
Weight: 4
Speed Factor: 4
Proficiency Type: Short Sword
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 5 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Cleric
 Druid
 Mage~

@200 = ~Cutlass~
@201 = ~The cutlass is a sword with a single-edged, curved, broad blade attached to a basket hilt. The blade is short and heavy. The sword is favored among pirate crews and is easily found in port communities, but is rare inland.

STATISTICS:

Damage: 1D6
Damage Type: Slashing
Weight: 4
Speed Factor: 5
Proficiency Type: Scimitar/Wakizashi/Ninja-To
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 8 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Cleric
 Mage~

@202 = ~Weighted Sack~
@203 = ~This rather unusual-looking device consists of a leather sack weighted with something heavy, probably lead. The sack is knotted at the neck and a strap extends around from there. Due to its size and shape, it might make more of a useful weapon rather than a pouch for carrying valuables.~

@204 = ~Blackjack~
@205 = ~This weapon is known by many names - most commonly a blackjack, but sometimes a "sap," "cosh" or even "life preserver" to those knowledgeable about its uses. This small, easily-concealed weapon consists of a leather-wrapped lead weight attached to a flexible leather strap reinforced with a coil spring. When used correctly, the blackjack inflicts minimal damage, but knocks out enemies instead of killing them. Thus, the weapon is considered a "humane approach" by thieves who wish to relieve the unfortunate victims of their valuables without resorting to murder.

STATISTICS:

THAC0: +2
Damage: 1D3 - 1
Special: 25% chance to render target unconscious
Damage type: fists
Weight: 5
Speed Factor: 5
Proficiency Type: Club
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 10 Dexterity
Usable By:
 All~

@206 = ~Lockpick~
@207 = ~A lockpick is an essential thief's tool. It is a small slender pin made of some type of metal, with various bends or serrations used to open a lock in the absence of the proper key.~

@208 = ~Bronze Lockpick~
@209 = ~This is a small, slender length of bronze with one end bent and flattened. It is an essential tool to the shrewd thief who wishes to open locks without having access to the proper keys. This lockpick is quite simple and made of bronze. It is probably suitable to open locks of low resistance but will likely fail on locks of even medium difficulty, unless the "locksmith" is truly skilled indeed.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability: Open Locks +10%
Requires: 10 Dexterity
Usable By:
 Thief~

@210 = ~Mask~
@211 = ~A mask is a covering typically worn over the eyes and sometimes the entire face. Its purpose is usually to obscure the identity of the wearer from prying eyes. Other masks are worn for protective or ritual purposes and may play roles in special holidays or priestly ceremonies.~

@212 = ~Mask of Evasion~
@213 = ~Arguably, the best way to avoid pursuit is to be unrecognizable. The embroidered mask has the ability to cast a dweomer about a thief's immediate surroundings. This enchantment makes it so the average person won't look twice at the wearer, a benefit of inestimable worth to one in the larcenous profession. It has, however, only limited uses before passersby catch on to the disguise and also tends to wear out after a while.

Equipped Ability: Protects against critical hits
Special: Stealth +50%
Weight: 1
Usable By:
 Thief~

@214 = ~Bracelet~
@215 = ~A bracelet is a piece of jewelry worn around the wrist. Typically, bracelets are made of metal bands or chain; others are strings of beads or gems. Some bracelets are enchanted to have protective powers.~

@216 = ~Bracelet of Wisdom~
@217 = ~This string of silvery pearls is said to have been consecrated by the sea elves to Deep Sashelas, Lord of the Undersea. It gives its wearer a bonus to her wisdom and also the ability to cure disease three times a day.

Equipped Ability: Wisdom +1
Special: Cure Disease (3 per day)
Weight: 1~

@218 = ~Bastard Sword +2, Iceblade~
@219 = ~This finely-crafted blade feels cold to the touch and stretches nearly five feet long. Strange runes reach along its fuller starting from the crossguard, stating an unknown legend in the northern tongue. The runic legend has imparted some properties of the sword's homeland to its bearer. The hand-and-a-half hilt is wrapped with sturdy cross-hatched leather and weighted with a simple iron pommel in the shape of a medallion.

STATISTICS:

THAC0: +2
Damage: 2D4 + 2
 10% chance +1 point of cold damage
Armor Class: +1 bonus
Equipped Ability: Cold Resistance +10%
Damage type: slashing
Weight: 7
Speed Factor: 6
Proficiency Type: Bastard Sword
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 11 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Druid
 Cleric
 Mage
 Thief~

@220 = ~Brooch~
@221 = ~Brooches are decorative jewelry items designed to be attached to garments and worn at or near the neck. Most brooches are made of metal, often silver or gold but sometimes bronze or another material. Brooches are frequently decorated with enamel or gemstones. They may be worn solely for ornament or serve a practical function such as a cloak fastener. Some brooches are even enchanted for a special purpose.~

@222 = ~Brooch of Tempus~
@223 = ~This ornate brooch is worked in the shape of a braided pin with a fearsome head adorning it. Attached to this is a torc ending in two other heads. The whole piece is forged from a bronze alloy and enameled with gold, and is designed to be worn at the neck as a cloak or dress fastener. The point of the brooch vaguely resembles a flaming sword or dagger. As such, it is symbolic of faith in Tempus. Some of his elite Battleguard are said to wear brooches of this nature, and the Lord of Battles grants a boon of inspiration to such worthy followers.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability: Memorize 1 extra 2nd level priest spell
Requires: 14 Wisdom
Usable By:
  Cleric (Neutral or Chaotic only)~

@224 = ~Battle Axe +2, Armor Biter~
@225 = ~This axe from the northlands is a bit heavier than a belt or hand axe. The antiquated axe head is carved with an intricate pattern. It is also "bearded," indicating an increased length at the lower end of the blade, adding rigidity to the weapon for chopping tasks. The beard is also handy for hooking the edge of enemy shields. Northland warriors decorate their weapons with runic characters which identify the owner. Because the Northlanders believe the runes are magical, this make the weapon stronger in battle.

STATISTICS:

THAC0: +2
Damage: 1D8 + 2
Special: 5% chance to hook enemy's shield or limb
 (-1 penalty to AC of target for 5 rounds)
Damage type: slashing
Weight: 5
Speed Factor: 5
Proficiency Type: Axe
Type: 1-handed
Requires: 10 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Druid
 Cleric
 Mage
 Thief~

@226 = ~Helm of the North~
@227 = ~This well-crafted helm is embossed with an intricate pattern across and around the crown and nose guard. The hinged cheek plates are embellished with traditional wolf designs. This extraordinary example has ritual significance to the Northlanders.

STATISTICS:

Armor Class Bonus: None
Equipped Abilities:
 Protects against critical hits
 Cold Resistance +20%
Weight: 2
Not Usable By:
 Mage
 Thief~

@228 = ~Staff of Swarming Insects +2~
@229 = ~This staff is extremely gnarled and apparently made of two different types of wood grown together. Much of its length is covered with finely done carvings depicting winged biting and stinging insects (bees, deerflies, horseflies, wasps and the like). Any priest character (cleric or druid) holding it can command the staff to create a swarm of such insects, at the same time expending one of the staff's charges.

STATISTICS:

Abilities (one charge):
Insect Plague
 Damage: 1 HP every 2 seconds for 6 rounds
 Special: Spell failure; fear
 Range: Sight

THAC0: +2 bonus
Damage: 1D6 + 2
Damage type: crushing
Weight: 3
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: Blunt Weapons
Type: 2-handed
Requires: 5 Strength
Usable By:
 Cleric
 Druid~

@230 = ~Ring of Immunity~
@231 = ~This ring gives immunity to all spells, attacks and detections for permanently invisible creatures.~

@232 = ~Great Elixir~
@233 = ~Of all the tales of powerful magic that have emerged from Halruaa, the legend of the great elixirs is perhaps the most remarkable. The first great elixir concoction possibly originated in Netheril itself. Regardless of their origins, these liquids possessed a chaotic nature that made them an unappealing risk. The formula for their creation was eventually lost and forgotten. Some caches of the unpredictable stuff do pop up every once in a while, however.

A great elixir is a translucent, aquamarine liquid that twinkles and swirls gently about in endless motion. It is described as tasting like fine wine on fire. The possible effects of any given elixir are random, ranging from instant death to the attainment of one or more innate abilities.

Special: Unknown (random permanent effect)
Weight: 1~

@234 = ~Mahogany Shoe Box~
@235 = ~Karaea designed this box to hold her many shoes and boots. It is compact, sturdy and made of a varnished mahogany bound with iron. She had a wizard friend enchant it so that it opens onto another self-contained mini-plane. A large quantity of boots may be placed in the box, yet its weight stays the same.

STATISTICS:

Capacity: 40 boots or shoes
Weight: 2~

@236 = ~Ebony Shoe Box~
@237 = ~This box is designed to hold many shoes and boots. It is compact, sturdy and made of a varnished ebony bound with iron. A wizard enchanted it so that it opens onto another self-contained mini-plane. A large quantity of boots may be placed in the box, yet its weight stays the same.

STATISTICS:

Capacity: 40 boots or shoes
Weight: 2~

@238 = ~Carnival Melee Weapons~
@239 = ~Black Lily's Shop~
@240 = ~Shop of Silence~

@241 = ~Good day!~ [T-SVA01A] //SELECT_COMMON1
@242 = ~Yes.~ [T-SVA01B] //SELECT_COMMON2
@243 = ~I really need to talk to you.~ [T-SVA01C] //SELECT_COMMON3
@244 = ~Ho ha ha ha!~ [T-SVA01D] //SELECT_COMMON4
@245 = ~Kill that scum! Get 'em good!~ [T-SVA02A] //BATTLE_CRY1
@246 = ~Blood and bloody hell!~ [T-SVA02B] //BATTLE_CRY2
@247 = ~My powers shall obliterate you!~ [T-SVA02C] //BATTLE_CRY1
@248 = ~Die!~ [T-SVA02D] //BATTLE_CRY2
@249 = ~So long!~ [T-SVA03A] //MORALE

@250 = ~Goblin Boots~
@251 = ~Over a century ago, the goblin shaman Kemunshalzeka bound a fearsome vampiric wolf to serve her. In a fierce battle with the wood elves, a flurry of enchanted arrows slew the wolf. Kemunshalzeka defeated the elves with her powerful magic and after the battle, skinned the wolf's corpse to make these boots. Of course, none of this truly stopped the wolf, being an undead creature. Indeed, the wearer of these boots can once again summon up the wolf when needed. Even if killed, the wolf will be able to rise again after the next sunset. Additionally, the boots protect the wearer from most wolves, though not werewolves.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability: Immune to wolf attacks
Special: Summon Vampiric Wolf once per day
Weight: 2~

@252 = ~Help! Help!~ [T-SVA03B] //MORALE
@253 = ~I am wounded! Heal me!~ [T-SVA07] //HURT
@254 = ~You're in GREAT peril if you bother me. Just you wait!~ [T-SVA08] //DIALOGUE_HOSTILE

@255 = ~Goblin Archer~
@256 = ~Goblin Bodyguard~
@257 = ~Goblin Elite Archer~
@258 = ~Goblin Chief~
@259 = ~Goblin Shaman~
@260 = ~Gnome Slave~
@261 = ~Svirfneblin Ring~

@262 = ~Chained-Teeth Earrings~
@263 = ~The chains of these earrings appear to be fashioned from a black, otherworldly metal. Attached to these are the long, narrow teeth of some strange creature. Upon closer examination, you discover these thin metal earrings are actually a pair of well-crafted lockpicks. If need be, the wearer can use them to pick open stubborn locks.

Equipped Abilities:
 Open Locks +5%
 Protects against critical hits
Requires: 10 Dexterity
Usable By:
 Thief~

@264 = ~Iron Lockpick Set~
@265 = ~This is a set of well-crafted lockpicks of different shapes that can be used to open a variety of locks from the easy to the difficult. One of the implements can also be used to find and disarm traps. Although not nearly as valuable to intrepid locksmiths as the rare and highly-coveted mithril or adamantite lockpicks, this is a very serviceable set.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Abilities:
 Open Locks +15%
 Find/Disarm Traps +5%
Requires: 10 Dexterity
Usable By:
 Thief~

@266 = ~Pile of Bones~
@267 = ~This heap of decaying bones is all that remains of some poor, luckless adventurer. There are few clues as to whom this person was, but he or she was probably human, elven or a similarly-sized humanoid. Without doubt, the adventurer met a violent end, judging from the cut marks and shattering of the bones. Likely, many years have also transpired since this occurred, perhaps even centuries, if the color and condition of the bones give any indication.

STATISTICS:

Weight: 15~

@268 = ~Tattered Note~
@269 = ~This is an aged and torn piece of vellum covered with the dust of bones and the bloodstains of a corpse long since decayed. Despite its condition, a portion of it is barely readable.

"...maist interesting t' the elders... happened upon what appears t' be a cave... many cunning contrivances what make it appear... pairt of the surrounding rock... I hope the vermin I threw off m' trail last night d' not lair in this befoul'd place... mayhaps the fabled shield of Gwalhaudh lies... shall see presentish..."~

@270 = ~Knight's Shield +1~
@271 = ~Although many cracks of age or heavy use appear on the surface of this shield, they do not appear to weaken it the slightest. The shield appears to be bronze, though much stronger perhaps even than iron. Moreover, it shows no signs of the green coating of verdigris that would usually cover a bronze object of any age. It must be forged of some alloy unknown to modern metalsmiths. The shield is the tri-corner shape typical of the knight's shield in the classical style, bisected with a cross of darker alloy and embossed with a quartered blazon of castles and rampant crowned lions. It was clearly the shield of a knight of renown, possibly even a duke or king. Perhaps this is even the legendary shield of Gwalhaudh the Pure, lost many ages ago. The shield supposedly could keep evil creatures at bay, for they were loath to touch it or even come near it.

STATISTICS:

Armor Class Bonus: 2
Equipped Ability: Protection From Evil
Weight: 6
Requires: 12 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Bard
 Druid
 Mage
 Thief
 Evil-aligned characters~

@272 = ~Wolf Attribute Item~
@273 = ~This item gives the wolf its innate features like slow regeneration.~

@274 = ~Drow Boots~
@275 = ~Soon after the Descent, the drow started making these boots in the craftshops of the Underdark. The dark elf craftsmiths started by making copies of elven boots and warping them, based on the materials they had available to them. Unlike other drow items, the boots are not made with adamantine, and therefore will not degrade in the light. Rather, they're made with enchanted spider silk which gives the wearer immunity to webs. In addition, the boots confer the ability to call up a myrlochar, or "soul spider," regardless of where the wearer may be. These dark otherplanar servants of Lolth have the ability to permanently drain hit points from their targets and transfer the stolen health to themselves.

STATISTICS

Equipped Abilities:
 Move Silently: +15%
 Immune to Web
Special: Summon Myrlochar once per day
Weight: 3~

@276 = ~Daemonfey Boots~
@277 = ~Six thousand years ago, a proud clan of sun elves dwelt in what is now Cormanthor. These ambitious elves trafficked with demons to gain power and bred with them to strengthen their bloodline. Eventually, other elves learned of this outrage and destroyed the half-fiends of House Dlardrageth. Some survived to breed with other daemonkin, spawning the fey'ri tieflings and similar abominations. Fewer yet of the original lineage escaped the initial battle and vanished from history in the forests of the North. These demon-blooded elves bred with other elves and eventually became known as daemonfey. Their boots are imbued with infernal power that can summon an abysmal ally. Sometimes this has grave consequences for the wearer.

STATISTICS

Equipped Abilities:
 Magic Resistance: +10%
 Movement rate +4
Special:
 Summon Cambion or Alu-Fiend once per day (25% chance hostile)
 Temporary level drain for 8 turns (50% chance)
Not Usable By:
 Lawful characters
Weight: 3~

@278 = ~Tiger's Eye Gem~
@279 = ~Tiger's Eye is a dark brown agate with rich golden-brown striping that gives the stone its name. Legends state that tiger's eye is useful in repelling spirits. While this is not known to be true, the agate is ground and used both in preparing potions and in creating magical markings.~

@280 = ~Snowflake Obsidian~
@281 = ~This obsidian variety occurs here and there in the Realms in large deposits of volcanic origin. It is black with grayish flower-like patches that often, especially if some stone can be cut away, radiate symmetrical patterns that resemble snowflakes. It is brittle and weak, but often used for small carvings. In the Realms, it is either finished to tumbled gemstone form for sale, or sold in "trade blocks" or large irregular chunks.~

@282 = ~Amethyst Gem~
@283 = ~This mineral forms in deep purple crystals, often times in the middle of geodes but also in large veins on the surface, sometimes stretching for hundreds of feet. While most specimens have minor imperfections or traces of other minerals clouding them, some few are free from such defects and are cut into high-quality gemstones. Amethysts are supposed to ward off drunkenness, and as such are usually used as ornaments for mugs and chalices, particularly those used by nobility. This ward is more superstition than truth.~

@284 = ~Topaz Gem~
@285 = ~Topaz is a golden, transparent gemstone found in large crystals in granite deposits. Usually yellow or brown, it becomes pink if exposed to great temperatures. Topaz is very hard and wears well. It is used as an inset gem in devices which offer protection from magical effects.~

@286 = ~Amber Gem~
@287 = ~Amber is a golden, fossilized resin, usually tumbled smooth and cut cabochon. It is soft and brittle and often used as a good luck charm to ward off diseases and plague. Some amber contains other preserved fossils, such as primitive plants and insects. These variants are valued much higher in the Realms. Amber pellets strung on thongs are used as a medium of trade by northern barbarians, but are graded among civilized folk for their gem value.~

@288 = ~Fire Opal~
@289 = ~This fiery orange-red opal is usually solid but sometimes has gold or green flecks. The translucent gem is often cut into faceted jewels the same way sapphires and rubies are. It is found near active hot springs and geysers, and is often used to make jewelry such as pendants or rings.~

@290 = ~Bandfire Opal~
@291 = ~Bandfire is the name given to a type of precious opal with mottled or wavy bands showing a play of colors. Highly coveted by ancient elf clans, it has become somewhat uncommon in recent times. This pale, smooth gemstone is sometimes used in scrying or protective devices.~

@292 = ~This is an ordinary, medium-sized, hand-held mirror.~
@293 = ~This is a medium-sized, hand-held mirror with a tin alloy frame. It presents an exceptionally clear reflection, so the metal behind the glass may be of silver. Though impractical as a normal defense, anyone bearing this mirror as a shield has a chance of reflecting the gaze attacks of basilisks and other such creatures.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability:
 25% chance to reflect gaze attacks
Weight: 1~

@294 = ~This sturdy wooden box is enameled with lacquer and clasped with bronze. It is small but serviceable, and can hold a few smaller items.

STATISTICS:

Capacity: 12 items
Weight: 5~

@295 = ~Boots of Swift Love~
@296 = ~These boots are retailored from the Stylish Boots of the Cheetah and the shoes known as "Love Lies Bleeding," in which it really is possible to knock 'em dead. The original Paws of the Cheetah were the property of deadly assassins fond of chasing down their prey. They moved with such speed that their targets often didn't have the opportunity to respond, even on horseback. This was very impressive, of course, but the assassins had no sense of style. This pair is fashioned in a more attractive cheetah-skin pattern, dyed red and inset with fire opal. They increase the wearer's speed and look good at the same time.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability: Movement rate doubled
Special: Cast Nature's Beauty once per day
Weight: 3~

@297 = ~Stinking Gnomish Boots~
@298 = ~These low boots have been recobbled from the sturdy Gnomish Boots and the infamous boots known as "Stinky Feet." The latter acquired their name from the original wearer who, after several years of snide remarks and requests that he sit somewhere else, anywhere else, decided to take advantage of his situation. The boots have been fully cleaned and inset with amber. They still bear the title "Stinking" but out of deepest respect for their power. The toes point upward slightly, and the gnomish soles are also designed to keep a sure footing on any terrain, whether underground or on the surface.

Equipped Ability: Free Action
Special: Cast Stinking Cloud once per day
Weight: 2~

@299 = ~Thrice-Armored Boots~
@300 = ~These boots get their name from their unique three-color pattern, though they are actually refashioned from four pairs of boots. These include everyday boots of green, yellow and blue and the Boots of Avoidance known as "Senses of the Cat." The magic of these boots was specifically designed to detect incoming missiles and aid the wearer in avoiding them. They were originally commissioned by the instructor of an archery academy, who had tired of suffering "accidents" at the hands of his inexperienced students. In addition, they provide a lesser armor class protection to other types of attacks. The boots are studded with multi-colored bandfire opal. Rumor has it that jesters prize these boots quite highly.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Ability: AC -2, -5 vs. missiles
Weight: 4~

@301 = ~Drow Boots of the Night~
@302 = ~Soon after the Descent, the drow started making these boots in the craftshops of the Underdark. The dark elf craftsmiths started by making copies of elven boots and warping them, based on the materials they had available to them. Unlike other drow items, the boots are not made with adamantine, and therefore will not degrade in the light. Rather, they're made with an enchanted spider silk that gives the wearer immunity to webs. In addition, the boots confer the ability to call up a myrlochar, or "soul spider," regardless of where the wearer may be. These dark otherplanar servants of Lolth have the ability to permanently drain hit points from their targets and transfer the stolen health to themselves. The boots have been combined with the Boots of Elvenkind to confer the original abilities of their prototype. They also haste the wearer and are inset with amethyst of deepest purple.

STATISTICS

Equipped Abilities:
 Move Silently: +30%
 Hide in Shadows: +15%
 Movement rate doubled
 Immune to Web
Special: Summon Myrlochar twice per day
Weight: 3~

@303 = ~Daemon Noble Boots~
@304 = ~Six thousand years ago, a proud clan of sun elves dwelt in what is now Cormanthor. These ambitious elves trafficked with demons to gain power and bred with them to strengthen their bloodline. Eventually, other elves learned of this outrage and destroyed the half-fiends of House Dlardrageth. Some survived to breed with other daemonkin, spawning the fey'ri tieflings and similar abominations. Fewer yet of the original lineage escaped the initial battle and vanished from history in the forests of the North. These demon-blooded elves bred with other elves and eventually became known as daemonfey. Their boots are imbued with infernal power that can summon an abysmal ally. These particular boots have been retailored with the Boots of Speed and a star ruby of unparalleled beauty, making them suitable footwear for a demon prince.

STATISTICS

Equipped Abilities:
 Magic Resistance: +15%
 Movement rate doubled
Special: Summon Cambion or Alu-Fiend once per day
Not Usable By:
 Lawful characters
Weight: 3~

@305 = ~Mirrored Shield +1~
@306 = ~Originally, this shield appeared to be of weathered bronze, though much stronger perhaps even than iron. Moreover, it showed no signs of the green coating of verdigris that would usually cover a bronze object of any age. It must have been forged of some alloy unknown to modern metalsmiths. It has been given a reflective coating of silvery metal and diamond. The shield is the tri-corner shape typical of the knight's shield in the classical style, bisected with a cross of darker alloy and embossed with a quartered blazon of castles and rampant crowned lions. It was clearly the shield of a knight of renown, possibly even a duke or king. Perhaps this was even the legendary shield of Gwalhaudh the Pure, lost many ages ago. In addition to reflecting the gaze of creatures like basilisks, the shield can also keep evil creatures at bay, for they are loath to touch it or even come near it.

STATISTICS:

Armor Class Bonus: 2
Equipped Abilities:
 Protection From Evil
 Reflects gaze attacks
Weight: 6
Requires: 12 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Bard
 Druid
 Mage
 Thief
 Evil-aligned characters~

